00:21:05,710 --> 00:21:07,270
All those authors,

279
00:21:07,270 --> 00:21:08,750
they don't publish in the spring.

280
00:21:08,790 --> 00:21:09,910
I mean, they...

281
00:21:10,790 --> 00:21:12,470
Those are summer, fall guys.

282
00:21:12,710 --> 00:21:13,990
What can I tell ya?

283
00:21:14,030 --> 00:21:16,510
Maybe they got some extra ideas
this year.

284
00:21:16,550 --> 00:21:19,550
Some might've stockpiled novels
like squirrels.

285
00:21:19,590 --> 00:21:21,990
Hey, what did you used to call
those books you used to write

286
00:21:22,070 --> 00:21:23,710
when you were young and hungry,

287
00:21:23,750 --> 00:21:26,070
and were writing books faster
than they could print them?

288
00:21:26,110 --> 00:21:27,750
Trunk novels.

289
00:21:27,750 --> 00:21:30,590
That's right.
Trunk novels.

290
00:21:30,630 --> 00:21:32,150
Maybe those guys
dug up a few trunk novels

291
00:21:32,190 --> 00:21:33,590
and dusted them off.

292
00:21:33,630 --> 00:21:35,110
Figured, "what the hell," right?

293
00:21:35,110 --> 00:21:36,950
What are you asking me, Marty?

294
00:21:37,030 --> 00:21:40,550
Scribner wants to publish
a novel late winter.

295
00:21:40,590 --> 00:21:42,310
What does that mean?

296
00:21:42,350 --> 00:21:47,150
Pages with your name on them
by the end of the summer.

297
00:21:47,670 --> 00:21:50,750
You're asking me to write
a novel in three months, Marty?

298
00:21:50,910 --> 00:21:51,270
No, no, no.

299
00:21:51,310 --> 00:21:52,710
You wouldn't have
to turn in the manuscript

300
00:21:52,750 --> 00:21:54,790
until end of September
or early October.

301
00:21:55,150 --> 00:21:56,390
'Course that means they'd really

302
00:21:56,390 --> 00:21:57,750
have to crash their production,

303
00:21:58,110 --> 00:21:59,630
but they can do it.

304
00:21:59,670 --> 00:22:04,470
The question is whether
or not you can do it.

305
00:22:04,470 --> 00:22:06,150
So what do you say?

306
00:22:06,230 --> 00:22:10,550
Can you write your next novel
on this ridiculous schedule?

307
00:22:10,590 --> 00:22:12,190
I can do it, Marty.

308
00:22:12,230 --> 00:22:13,830
Attaboy, Mike.

309
00:22:13,910 --> 00:22:16,870
Well, you get clickety cranking
on your next Noonan blockbuster,

310
00:22:16,910 --> 00:22:18,350
and I'm going to get
to gouging these guys

311
00:22:18,390 --> 00:22:19,750
for every penny they have,

312
00:22:19,790 --> 00:22:21,670
for breaking your balls
and making you rush

313
00:22:21,710 --> 00:22:22,910
your next novel like this.

314
00:22:22,950 --> 00:22:24,630
Okay, Marty, that sounds good.

315
00:22:24,630 --> 00:22:26,190
All right.

316
00:22:26,230 --> 00:22:27,550
Oh, and do me a favor, will ya?

317
00:22:27,630 --> 00:22:28,790
Yeah?

318
00:22:28,870 --> 00:22:30,790
Take it easy on the drinking, will ya?

319
00:22:30,830 --> 00:22:32,510
Yeah, yeah.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

320
00:22:32,550 --> 00:22:33,630
[Phone beeps]

321
00:22:33,710 --> 00:22:35,110
[Sighs]

322
00:22:39,390 --> 00:22:41,710
[Breathes deeply]

323
00:22:53,630 --> 00:22:55,510
You're not disappointed in me?

324
00:22:55,510 --> 00:22:57,190
Hmm?

325
00:22:57,230 --> 00:23:01,950
Once for "yes,"
twice for "no."

326
00:23:02,030 --> 00:23:02,670
Hmm?

327
00:23:38,870 --> 00:23:42,830
Last night I dreamt I went
to Dark Score Lake again.

328
00:23:53,430 --> 00:23:56,270
[Heart beating]

329
00:24:00,630 --> 00:24:03,270
[Shrill screaming]

330
00:24:25,590 --> 00:24:26,910
[Distant child crying]

331
00:24:26,950 --> 00:24:29,830
[Distant screaming]

332
00:24:35,710 --> 00:24:37,110
[Phone ringing]

333
00:24:37,150 --> 00:24:40,910
Oh?

334
00:24:40,950 --> 00:24:43,950
[Sighs]

335
00:24:43,990 --> 00:24:45,270
Yeah?

336
00:24:45,310 --> 00:24:47,950
Mr. Noonan.

337
00:24:47,990 --> 00:24:49,710
Yeah?

338
00:24:49,750 --> 00:24:53,190
My name is Bill Dean,
from down on Dark Score Lake.

339
00:24:53,230 --> 00:24:56,030
I was helping your wife
renovate the property

340
00:24:56,070 --> 00:24:57,590
you inherited a couple years back?

341
00:24:57,630 --> 00:24:59,510
Okay.

342
00:24:59,550 --> 00:25:03,670
The local kids are getting
Wilder and Wilder every year.

343
00:25:03,670 --> 00:25:06,870
A bunch of them snuck
into your house the other night.

344
00:25:06,910 --> 00:25:09,830
At least the only thing
I can think of happening.

345
00:25:09,870 --> 00:25:11,790
Why?
Why is that?

346
00:25:11,830 --> 00:25:15,310
Well, it's the windows.

347
00:25:15,350 --> 00:25:17,950
They're all broken
from the inside out.

348
00:25:18,030 --> 00:25:21,790
Now I just wanted to make sure
you'll approve the expenses

349
00:25:21,830 --> 00:25:23,190
of getting them fixed.

350
00:25:23,230 --> 00:25:24,630
This goes a little beyond

351
00:25:24,630 --> 00:25:26,390
the normal caretaking
your wife hired me for.

352
00:25:26,430 --> 00:25:27,670
Yeah, yeah, yeah, sure.

353
00:25:27,750 --> 00:25:29,190
Well, do whatever it takes.
Of course.

354
00:25:29,270 --> 00:25:31,390
Um, listen, Mr. Dean,

355
00:25:31,390 --> 00:25:33,590
how is the lake house?

356
00:25:33,590 --> 00:25:35,230
I mean, apart from the windows,
of course.

357
00:25:35,270 --> 00:25:37,710
She's fine.
How come?

358
00:25:37,750 --> 00:25:39,710
Oh, I was just thinking

359
00:25:39,790 --> 00:25:41,590
of maybe getting away
for a while, that's all.

360
00:25:41,630 --> 00:25:47,590
You... you want me to get
it ready for an extended stay?

361
00:25:47,630 --> 00:25:50,710
Yes.

362
00:25:50,710 --> 00:25:52,630
Yes, let's... let's...
Let's do that, Bill.

363
00:25:52,630 --> 00:25:53,910
That would be great.
I appreciate it.

364
00:25:53,950 --> 00:25:55,390
Thank you.

365
00:25:55,430 --> 00:25:59,910
She'll be ready for you,
Mr. Noonan.

366
00:26:01,710 --> 00:26:06,030
I think it's a good idea,
don't you, Jo?

367
00:26:06,750 --> 00:26:08,550
Once for "yes,"
twice for "no."

368
00:26:10,870 --> 00:26:12,790
All right, let's go.

369
00:26:12,870 --> 00:26:14,510
[Groans]

370
00:26:14,510 --> 00:26:15,790
Oh.

371
00:26:17,350 --> 00:26:18,470
[Sighs]

372
00:26:24,070 --> 00:26:26,070
[Telephone rings once]

373
00:27:06,830 --> 00:27:08,870
<i>"Now arriving at Dark Score Lake."</i>

374
00:27:10,290 --> 00:27:11,530
[Turns radio off]

375
00:27:43,450 --> 00:27:46,130
[Sighs]

376
00:27:46,490 --> 00:27:47,450
Wake up, Jo.

377
00:28:26,650 --> 00:28:29,530
[Foreboding music]

378
00:28:31,010 --> 00:28:33,570
[crickets chirping]

379
00:28:38,250 --> 00:28:41,650
Last night I dreamt I went
to Dark Score Lake again.

380
00:28:44,570 --> 00:28:45,130
[Door slams]

381
00:28:46,530 --> 00:28:47,370
Hello?

382
00:28:48,010 --> 00:28:48,810
Mr. Noonan.

383
00:28:50,570 --> 00:28:51,290
Bill Dean.

384
00:28:51,810 --> 00:28:53,370
Oh, good evening, Bill.

385
00:28:54,170 --> 00:28:55,650
Yeah, please call me Mike.

386
00:28:55,690 --> 00:28:57,450
I didn't mean to scare you.

387
00:28:57,490 --> 00:28:59,090
I just thought you'd like
someone here to greet you

388
00:28:59,090 --> 00:29:00,330
when you arrived.

389
00:29:00,370 --> 00:29:02,690
Oh, thanks very much.
I appreciate it.

390
00:29:02,730 --> 00:29:05,970
You look just like your
granddad, Harold.

391
00:29:06,050 --> 00:29:07,850
I do?

392
00:29:07,890 --> 00:29:10,330
Yup.

393
00:29:10,370 --> 00:29:12,370
Can I help you with your luggage?

394
00:29:12,370 --> 00:29:13,610
Yeah, sure, sure.

395
00:29:13,650 --> 00:29:16,250
I don't have much, but thank you.

396
00:29:16,330 --> 00:29:19,090
[Eerie music]

397
00:29:36,210 --> 00:29:38,050
yeah, just put that over there, Bill.

398
00:29:38,130 --> 00:29:38,810
Thanks.

399
00:29:40,250 --> 00:29:43,090
Oh, Jo really did a lot of work
to the place, didn't she?

400
00:29:43,250 --> 00:29:45,330
Yeah, she sure did.

401
00:29:49,050 --> 00:29:51,770
[Chuckles]

402
00:29:53,370 --> 00:29:54,050
Bunter.

403
00:29:55,450 --> 00:29:56,410
Jo named him.

404
00:29:56,610 --> 00:29:59,050
It's the first thing we bought
when we inherited the place.

405
00:29:59,130 --> 00:30:01,770
Got it in a little antique store
outside of town.

406
00:30:01,970 --> 00:30:02,410
[Laughs]

407
00:30:02,850 --> 00:30:04,490
When we got frisky here,

408
00:30:05,970 --> 00:30:09,130
she said we were ringing
Bunter's bell.

409
00:30:09,170 --> 00:30:11,210
[Laughing]

410
00:30:13,850 --> 00:30:15,570
Uh, look, I better be off.

411
00:30:15,610 --> 00:30:16,810
Okay.

412
00:30:17,050 --> 00:30:20,810
Oh, I left my number on the fridge,

413
00:30:20,850 --> 00:30:23,170
along with the number
of the local cleaning lady

414
00:30:23,210 --> 00:30:25,010
your wife hired...
Brenda Meserve.

415
00:30:25,050 --> 00:30:26,370
- Mm-hmm.

416
00:30:26,410 --> 00:30:28,730
Told her she ought
to come by tomorrow,

417
00:30:28,770 --> 00:30:30,010
if that's okay with you.

418
00:30:30,090 --> 00:30:31,290
Great, great.

419
00:30:31,370 --> 00:30:33,130
Good night, now.

420
00:30:33,170 --> 00:30:38,410
You bet.

421
00:30:38,450 --> 00:30:40,570
Mr. Noonan.
Hmm?

422
00:30:40,570 --> 00:30:43,770
I was awful sorry
to hear of Jo's passing.

423
00:30:43,850 --> 00:30:45,290
Right.

424
00:30:45,290 --> 00:30:47,610
We all were.

425
00:30:47,690 --> 00:30:49,370
People around here, they...

426
00:30:50,610 --> 00:30:52,010
Really liked her, didn't they?

427
00:30:55,010 --> 00:30:55,890
They did.

428
00:30:57,330 --> 00:30:59,050
Well, good night,
Mr. Noonan.

429
00:30:59,490 --> 00:31:01,250
Good night Bill.

430
00:31:02,690 --> 00:31:03,610
Good night, now.

431
00:31:05,850 --> 00:31:07,250
[Keys clank]

432
00:31:07,290 --> 00:31:09,530
[Sighs]

433
00:31:17,210 --> 00:31:20,890
Hmm.

434
00:31:20,970 --> 00:31:23,770
[Playing guitar]

435
00:31:36,610 --> 00:31:39,450
[Melancholy music]

436
00:33:20,850 --> 00:33:22,170
Come to me.

437
00:33:24,010 --> 00:33:26,170
I have so much to show you, Mike.

438
00:33:44,170 --> 00:33:46,090
[Keys jingle]

439
00:34:03,090 --> 00:34:04,970
[Sighs]

440
00:35:09,970 --> 00:35:11,810
[Jazz music]

441
00:35:24,890 --> 00:35:26,130
let's fire it up.

442
00:35:36,930 --> 00:35:38,570
[Cracks knuckles]

443
00:35:48,330 --> 00:35:50,010
Mm-hmm.

444
00:35:53,650 --> 00:35:55,210
[Sighs]

445
00:35:55,650 --> 00:35:57,930
Come on now, something,
something, anything.

446
00:36:08,810 --> 00:36:10,130
Something!
Come on!

447
00:36:10,170 --> 00:36:12,650
Just give it to me!
Something!

448
00:36:17,650 --> 00:36:19,330
Okay, Jo.

449
00:36:22,170 --> 00:36:24,250
Tell me how to write, hmm?

450
00:36:24,290 --> 00:36:27,010
Just tell me how to write.

451
00:36:27,010 --> 00:36:29,730
[Bell rings]

452
00:36:36,210 --> 00:36:38,210
Bunter?

453
00:36:38,290 --> 00:36:41,130
[Foreboding music]

454
00:36:56,930 --> 00:36:59,490
[bell softly rings]

455
00:37:08,170 --> 00:37:10,730
[Continues ringing]

456
00:37:14,970 --> 00:37:17,890
[Clears throat]

457
00:37:32,050 --> 00:37:34,370
[Scoffs]

458
00:37:46,250 --> 00:37:48,970
Okay.

459
00:37:49,010 --> 00:37:53,250
Okay, Bunter.
That's enough of that.

460
00:38:08,850 --> 00:38:10,810
[Bell rings]

461
00:38:13,770 --> 00:38:16,530
[Soft rock music]

462
00:38:23,570 --> 00:38:26,490
¶ there are clouds on the horizon ¶

463
00:38:26,810 --> 00:38:28,090
¶ so take a breath

464
00:38:28,090 --> 00:38:32,090
¶ you're in the calm
before the storm ¶

465
00:38:33,810 --> 00:38:36,570
¶ if only for a moment

466
00:38:36,970 --> 00:38:39,810
¶ close your eyes
and feel the thunder ¶

467
00:38:40,170 --> 00:38:44,810
¶ we can't hide
or run for cover anymore ¶

468
00:38:47,450 --> 00:38:53,130
¶ it's time to take a stand together ¶

469
00:38:53,210 --> 00:38:57,690
¶ oh, oh

470
00:38:57,770 --> 00:39:00,610
¶ hold on

471
00:39:00,730 --> 00:39:03,850
¶ 'cause the tide is strong ¶

472
00:39:03,930 --> 00:39:08,890
¶ it can't erase
the fire in her eyes ¶

473
00:39:10,410 --> 00:39:13,610
[sighs]

474
00:39:21,870 --> 00:39:23,150
Greetings, my dear lady.

475
00:39:24,550 --> 00:39:27,710
<i>Greetings, my green lady.</i>

476
00:39:28,230 --> 00:39:29,070
Huh.

477
00:39:37,150 --> 00:39:38,150
[Sighs]

478
00:39:50,150 --> 00:39:52,550
[Scraping]

479
00:40:02,670 --> 00:40:03,630
Oh!

480
00:40:03,630 --> 00:40:07,110
[Grunts]

481
00:40:38,350 --> 00:40:39,070
Jo?

482
00:40:41,870 --> 00:40:42,870
Is that you?

483
00:40:47,110 --> 00:40:48,350
Once for "yes."

484
00:40:51,030 --> 00:40:52,150
Twice for "no."

485
00:41:03,830 --> 00:41:05,110
[Bell rings once]

486
00:41:10,350 --> 00:41:14,110
[Laughs]

487
00:41:17,110 --> 00:41:19,030
Oh!

488
00:41:19,150 --> 00:41:23,190
[Sighs]

489
00:41:28,110 --> 00:41:29,790
You're here, aren't you, Jo?

490
00:41:31,670 --> 00:41:33,470
[Bell rings once]

491
00:41:39,190 --> 00:41:41,990
[Laughs]

492
00:41:50,790 --> 00:41:56,310
[Woman singing shrill note]

493
00:41:58,390 --> 00:42:03,030
[Groans]

494
00:42:03,110 --> 00:42:05,030
[Woman screams]

495
00:42:05,070 --> 00:42:07,990
[Bell ringing]

496
00:42:07,990 --> 00:42:13,510
[Screams]

497
00:42:13,510 --> 00:42:16,870
[Panting]

498
00:42:23,670 --> 00:42:26,070
We're not alone, are we, Jo?

499
00:42:26,150 --> 00:42:26,830
Huh?

500
00:42:30,070 --> 00:42:34,230
[Door creaks open]

501
00:42:34,310 --> 00:42:37,110
Jo, are you there?

502
00:42:41,430 --> 00:42:43,350
Hi.
Who are you?

503
00:42:43,430 --> 00:42:45,590
I'm sorry,
Mr. Noonan.

504
00:42:45,670 --> 00:42:46,550
Name's Brenda Meserve.

505
00:42:46,630 --> 00:42:49,990
Your housekeeper?

506
00:42:49,990 --> 00:42:51,350
I... I used the key
to let myself in.

507
00:42:51,430 --> 00:42:53,350
Yes.
[Chuckles]

508
00:42:53,430 --> 00:42:55,030
Oh, yes.
Of course.

509
00:42:55,110 --> 00:42:57,270
Oh, good.
Nice to meet you, Brenda.

510
00:42:57,350 --> 00:42:59,110
How are you?

511
00:42:59,150 --> 00:43:00,310
Uh, Bill said he told you
I'd be coming by today

512
00:43:00,390 --> 00:43:02,790
to clean the place up for you.

513
00:43:02,790 --> 00:43:05,990
I can come back at a better time
if you'd like.

514
00:43:05,990 --> 00:43:07,270
Oh, no, no, no, no, no.
It's all fine.

515
00:43:07,270 --> 00:43:08,470
Uh, I was just going to head into town

516
00:43:08,550 --> 00:43:09,430
and get something to eat.

517
00:43:09,510 --> 00:43:10,550
You're sure?

518
00:43:10,550 --> 00:43:12,070
Oh, absolutely.

519
00:43:12,070 --> 00:43:14,350
Any, uh...
Any suggestions?

520
00:43:14,390 --> 00:43:17,510
Buddy Jellison's cafe,
right there on main street.

521
00:43:17,510 --> 00:43:19,990
Can't go wrong ordering
the villageburger.

522
00:43:20,070 --> 00:43:22,710
Ah, good.
Thank you very much.

523
00:43:22,790 --> 00:43:27,990
Thanks for coming.

524
00:43:55,110 --> 00:43:57,510
Hey! Hey!
Get out of the road!

525
00:43:57,550 --> 00:43:59,510
[Horn honks]

526
00:43:59,590 --> 00:44:00,630
Hey, get out of here!
Come on, come on!

527
00:44:00,630 --> 00:44:03,270
What are you doing?

528
00:44:03,310 --> 00:44:04,910
Ky!

529
00:44:04,950 --> 00:44:07,470
Ky?
Is that your name?

530
00:44:07,510 --> 00:44:08,950
Like Kya?

531
00:44:09,030 --> 00:44:11,030
- [Panting]
- That's my mommy.

532
00:44:11,110 --> 00:44:13,350
Sweetheart, what were you thinking?

533
00:44:13,790 --> 00:44:15,390
- I wanted to go swimming!
- [Sighs]

534
00:44:16,230 --> 00:44:17,510
Her name's Kya?

535
00:44:18,870 --> 00:44:21,430
Kyra, but sometimes I call her Ky.

536
00:44:21,830 --> 00:44:22,990
Oh.

537
00:44:23,670 --> 00:44:26,070
- I'm... I'm Mattie Devore.
- Hi, Mattie.

538
00:44:26,350 --> 00:44:28,990
- I'm not a bad mother. I swear to God.
- No, I didn't say you were.

539
00:44:28,990 --> 00:44:30,350
Please don't mention this to anybody.

540
00:44:30,510 --> 00:44:32,350
We're... we're going through
a little bit of a hard time.

541
00:44:33,310 --> 00:44:35,190
Yeah, well, I think
it's a little late for that.

542
00:44:38,870 --> 00:44:39,550
Yeah.

543
00:44:40,110 --> 00:44:41,790
Well, thanks for saving
my little girl.

544
00:44:42,110 --> 00:44:43,750
I guess God sent you here
at the right time.

545
00:44:43,790 --> 00:44:45,630
God's got nothing to do with it.

546
00:44:45,670 --> 00:44:50,470
I was just going to Buddy
Jellison's for a hamburger.

547
00:44:50,510 --> 00:44:52,150
[Both chuckle]

548
00:44:52,190 --> 00:44:53,870
This is a little bit weird
for me, but, uh,

549
00:44:53,910 --> 00:44:56,390
you're one of my favorite writers.

550
00:44:56,470 --> 00:44:58,390
And I can't believe you just
